\par }}{\*\pnseclvl1\pnucrm\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\*\pnseclvl2\pnucltr\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\*\pnseclvl3\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\*\pnseclvl4\pnlcltr\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta )}}{\*\pnseclvl5\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxtb (}{\pntxta )}}{\*\pnseclvl6\pnlcltr\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxtb (}{\pntxta )}}{\*\pnseclvl7\pnlcrm\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxtb (}{\pntxta )}}{\*\pnseclvl8\pnlcltr\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxtb (}{\pntxta )}}{\*\pnseclvl9\pnlcrm\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxtb (}{\pntxta )}}\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1030\cgrid {\b\f1\lang1033 SDI-test signal generators, PT8602 & PT8603.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\f1\lang1033 
\par PT8602/PT8603 are single board digital video generators. They differs only in the available pattern possibilities. From a clock, line- and frame-pulse they generates a complete serial digital video signal. Sound with different levels and frequencies can be embedded in the signal. EDH (Error data handling) -codes can be calculated and inserted into the signal. A text generator can generate and insert up to 8 characters in the pattern. Text is inserted in upper right corner of the screen. The units have two parallel outputs. The outputs are supervised by a level detector, that gives alarm if the signal for some reason disappears. 
\par 
\par The selected signal can be time adjusted ± 1 field ( totally 625 lines or 525 lines) with a resolution of 1/27 }{\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 sec }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 64 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033  37 ns.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 SDI-test signal controller:}{\f1\lang1033  This unit is controlled by a }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 -controller. The }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 -controller interfaces to the master controller on Main Board via a two-wire serial bus and a reset wire. The video part of the generator is controlled by a clock signal and, for each system (625 lines and 525 lines), a line pulse (625 lines: FH_G; 525 lines: FH_M) and a color framing pulse. Color framing: 625 lines/525 lines: 2500/1050 lines between each pulse. (625 lines: F8_G; 525 lines: F4_M). The }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 -controller circuit consist of a }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 -controller V50, the program PROM, an address-latch and an E}{\f1\lang1033\super 2}{\f1\lang1033 -PROM. The latter contains calibration data.  
\par 
\par When power is switched on, the master controller detects presence of  SDI-test signal generator. When detected, the unit receives information of what to generate, pattern, text, sound status (frequency and amplitude), EDH on/off and timing. When this information is received, text-data are stored in dual port RAM (V59), sound data (if needed) are stored in RAM circuits (V56 & V57). When writing to the RAM, PS-bit (V50, pin 6) is high, else low.  Last a 11 bit word is written to H-OFFSET PORT. This word is the sample offset between incoming and generated line pulse. Line and field offset is generated by the }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 -controller, see later.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 Video generator:}{\f1\lang1033  A video pattern is build of a number of lines. The sequence of lines is calculated by the }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 -controller from timing information and interrupts VINT and HINT. The address to these lines is written to \ldblquote Line type register\rdblquote . A new number is written by the }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 -controller each line if it is necessary, i.e. a line different from the previous line is needed. Line type is 16 bits wide, first upper part is written to \ldblquote 8 MSB-DATA\rdblquote , V66, then 8 LSB\rquote s are written to V65. Output from }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 -controller is synchronized to video line in 16 bit register V67 and V68. 
\par 
\par Each line consists of 32 segments, each segment is 32 samples. A horizontal counter (H-counter) in V63 counts each line to 1727 (625 lines) or 1715 (525 lines). Outputs are H0 to H10. Line type register and upper 5 bits from H-counter addresses the segment address PROM, V69. Output from this PROM addresses segment data PROM\rquote s V79}{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 174 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 V81, producing a 20 bit word, representing 10 bit\rquote s Y(luminance) samples and multiplexed 10 bit\rquote s U and  V samples.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 Status port:}{\f1\lang1033  Additional information is needed for each line: 2 bits (}{\f6\lang1033 S0 }{\f1\lang1033 and }{\f6\lang1033 S1}{\f1\lang1033 ) are used to start text generator, one bit (}{\f6\lang1033 SYSSEL}{\f1\lang1033 ) is used to indicate which system to generate (625/50 or 525/59.95), 2 bits are used to handle the sound generator (}{\f6\lang1033 SOUND}{\f1\lang1033  and }{\f6\lang1033 3OR4}{\f1\lang1033 ), one bit is used to indicate field 1 or field 2 (}{\f6\lang1033 F2}{\f1\lang1033 ) and one bit is used to disable EDH-insertion.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 Text generator:}{\f1\lang1033  In lines with text added to the pattern, one or both of the text bit in STATUS PORT is set high. This starts a text line counter (4 bits) in V63 and addresses a text row in dual port RAM, V59. From H-counter 7 bits addresses the horizontal text row. Output from the RAM is a character. This character is used to address a PROM (V64) where the waveshape is stored. 3 bits from H-counter, 4 bits from text-line counter and one bit indicating field 2, gives the actual text amplitude at the PROM\rquote s output.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 Sound generator:}{\f1\lang1033  Sound data are stored in RAM and addressed by \lquote Sound address counter\rquote  in V63. When a new level or sound function is selected, new sound data for the new selection are stored in RAM (V56/V57) by the }{\f1\lang1033 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 109 \\f "Symbol" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f3\fs20}}}{\f1\lang1033 -controller. When }{\f6\lang1033 3OR4}{\f1\lang1033 , V73, pin 12 is low, 3 sound samples for each of the four channels are inserted. When }{\f6\lang1033 3OR4}{\f1\lang1033  is high, 4 samples are inserted. When no sound shall be inserted, }{\f6\lang1033 SOUND-}{\f1\lang1033 bit, V73 pin 13 is low.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 Data multiplexer / sound inserter:}{\f1\lang1033  V75 has four functions: It blanks luminance- and chroma-data when text shall be inserted. It adds text to luminance data. It multiplexes luminance- and chroma-data and it inserts sound into the 10-bit data stream. 
\par 
\par When }{\f6\lang1033 TXT7 }{\f1\lang1033 is high, luminance- and chroma data are blanked. Text (7 lower bits from text PROM) is always added to luminance data. After text-adder luminance- and chroma-data are multiplexed together. In this data stream sound is inserted. According to the 5 }{\i\f1\lang1033 Sound Status Bits }{\f1\lang1033 framing codes, group identification (group code), sound data or checksum is inserted. The checksum is calculated every line with sound insertions.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 EDH-inserter:}{\f1\lang1033  At the output on V75, [PI9..PI0] pin 21 to 9 a correct 10 bit SDI parallel signal is present. These ten bits are clocked into EDH-inserter V82. This circuit calculates and inserts EDH-codes to the data stream. Insertion takes place when EDH-bit (V73, pin 15) is low. When EDH-bit is high, data are clocked through without modification.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 Parallel to serial converter:}{\f1\lang1033  The ten bits are serialized in V76. Output from this circuit feeds the output amplifier V77. This amplifier contains 2 amplifiers which drives 2 output BNC-connectors. Signals on these connectors are identical but independent of each other. 
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 Level detector:}{\f1\lang1033  A level detector is connected, via transformers TR1 and TR2, directly to the output BNC\rquote s. For TR1: Signal from this transformer is rectified by D201 and V201A. The signal is then lowpass-filtered and amplified by V201B. This gives a, nearly, DC-voltage at TP201/TP205 on -1.3V when the signal is correct (output open or terminated). This voltage holds TP202 and XA1, pin 5 high. If signal at the BNC-connector  vanishes, e.g. amplifier\rquote s not working, the DC-voltage raises to 0V. Then V203B takes TP202 and XA1, pin 5 low, indicating an error. Similar function for TR2, V211, V213 & XA1, pin 6.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\lang1033 Test pins}{\f1\lang1033 :
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\fi-567\li567\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\lang1030\cgrid {\fs20\lang1033 TP5:\tab On this pin is a 27MHz clock signal, which is regenerated form incoming video data. This clock is 0.8V centered around 2.5V. Indicates whether serializer V76 is able to lock to incoming data or not.
\par 
\par TP6:\tab This pin is low when data words  00.x}{\fs20\lang1033\sub Hex }{\fs20\lang1033 and FF.x}{\fs20\lang1033\sub H ex }{\fs20\lang1033 are received, else high. On patterns without sound or EDH-codes, two low pulses will be present each line. These pulses indicate EAV and SAV.  
\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1030\cgrid {\f1\lang1033 
\par These two pins could be used to indicate whether V76 locks, or have a chance to lock, properly to incoming data stream or not.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\f1\lang1033 
